hands_on_practices.solution:
We apply the adiabatic energy balance: the loss of kinetic energy is gained as internal energy. Initially the fluid has kinetic energy and finally it is at rest, so $\Delta U = U_{final}-U_{initial} = -\Delta K = K_{initial}$.
Per unit mass this gives $\Delta u = \frac{K_{initial}}{m}$.
Compute the initial kinetic energy of the solid-body rotation:
$$
\begin{align*}
K_{initial} &=\int_V\frac{1}{2}\rho(\Omega_0 r)^2 dV \\
&= \frac{1}{2}\rho\Omega_0^2\int_0^H dz \int_0^{2\pi} d\theta \int_0^R r^3dr \\
&= \frac{1}{2}\rho\Omega_0^2 H (2\pi) \frac{R^4}{4} \\
&= \frac{\rho \pi H R^4 \Omega_0^2}{4}
\end{align*}
$$
The total mass is $m=\rho \pi R^2 H$.
Therefore the specific internal-energy increase is
$$
\begin{align*}
\Delta u &=\frac{K_{initial}}{m} \\
&=\frac{\rho \pi H R^4 \Omega_0^2/4}{\rho \pi R^2 H} \\
&=\frac{\Omega_0^2 R^2}{4}
\end{align*}
$$
